{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17629390","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17629390"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:06:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:06:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17270"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17270","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17270"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9960"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69662"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9960","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9960"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17270"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55114"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"10754"},{"type":"tags","id":"10755"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23346"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23433"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69662","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69662"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA population genetics study examines the inheritance of a single gene with two alleles (A and a). The frequency of allele A is 0.6 and allele a is 0.4.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the expected frequency of heterozygous individuals (Aa) in this population assuming Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["0.24","0.60","0.72","0.36","0.48"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EUnder Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium, the frequency of heterozygotes (Aa) is calculated using the formula 2pq, where p is the frequency of allele A (0.6) and q is the frequency of allele a (0.4). Therefore, \u003Cstrong\u003E0.48\u003C/strong\u003E (2 \u00d7 0.6 \u00d7 0.4) is the expected frequency of heterozygotes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe complete Hardy-Weinberg equation (p\u00b2 + 2pq + q\u00b2 = 1) predicts all genotype frequencies:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHomozygous dominant (AA) = p\u00b2 = 0.6\u00b2 = 0.36\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHeterozygous (Aa) = 2pq = 2(0.6)(0.4) = 0.48\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHomozygous recessive (aa) = q\u00b2 = 0.4\u00b2 = 0.16\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHardy-Weinberg equilibrium assumes random mating, no mutation, no selection, no migration, and a large population size. When these conditions are met, allele and genotype frequencies remain stable across generations.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The Hardy-Weinberg principle states that allele frequencies remain constant in a population unless specific disturbing influences occur.","The Hardy-Weinberg equation (p\u00b2 + 2pq + q\u00b2 = 1) predicts genotype frequencies in a population at equilibrium.","Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium requires random mating, no mutation, no selection, no migration, and a large population size."],"references":["Turnpenny PD, Ellard S. Emery\u0027s Elements of Medical Genetics E-Book: Elsevier Health Sciences; 2011"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55114"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17270"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55114","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55114"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-12T12:07:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-12T12:08:24+10:30